	<div align="center" class="main-content">
		<div class="spacer">
	</div><br>			<label class="collapse_ACT" for="_1"><font size="5px">Nac transcriptional activity</font></label>
				<input id="_1" type="checkbox">
				<div class="ACT"><br><ul><li>Abbreviations are as follows : KDO , 2-keto-3-deoxyoctulosonic acid ; GlcN , glucosamine ; Glc , glucose ; GlcNac , N-acetyl-glucosamine ; Gal , galactose ; Hep , heptose ; P , phosphate ( not shown in this diagram nor present in our model are ethanolamine , phosphoethanolamine and aminoarabinose groups ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16511120" target="_blank">16511120</a>]<br></li>
<li>These catalyze the assembly of the pentapeptide moiety through the successive addition of l-Ala , d-Glu , m-dpm or l-Lys , and d-Ala -- d-Ala to UDP-MurNac by MurC , MurD , MurE , and MurF enzymes , respectively ( m-dpm = meso-diaminopimelic acid ; UDP = uridine-5 ' - diphosphoryl ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16158456" target="_blank">16158456</a>]<br></li>
<li>M3 , GlucNAc-MurNAc-L-Ala-D-Glu-m-dap ; M4 , GlucNAc-MurNAc-L-Ala-D-Glu-m-dap-D-Ala ; M2 , GlucNAc-MurNAc-L-Ala-D-Glu ; MLpp , Gluc-NAc-MurNAc-L-Ala-D-Glu-m-dap - ( e ) - L-Lys-L-Arg ( lipoprotein-bound M3 ) ; D34 , GlucNAc-MurNAc-L-Ala-D-glu-m-dap-m-dap ( D-Ala ) - D-Glu-L-Ala-MurNAc-GlucNac ( dap -- dap cross-linked dimer ) ; D43 , GlucNAc-MurNAc-L-Ala-D-Glu-m-dap-D-Ala-m-dap-D-Glu-L-Ala-MurNAc-Gluc - Nac ; D44 , GlucNAc-MurNAc-L-Ala-D-glu-m-dap-D-Ala-m-dap ( D-Ala ) - D-Glu-L-Ala-MurNAc-GlucNac ; D4Lpp , GlucNAc-MurNAc-L-Ala-D-glu-m-dap-D-Ala-m-dap [ ( e ) - L-Lys-L-Arg ] - D-Glu-L-Ala-MurNAc-GlucNac ( lipoprotein-bound D43 ) ; T444 , GlucNAc-MurNAc-L-Ala-D-Glu-m-dap-D-Ala-m-dap - [ D-Ala-m-dap ( D-Ala ) - D-Glu-L-Ala MurNAc-GlucNac ] - D-Glu-L-Ala-MurNAc-GlucNac .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12354237" target="_blank">12354237</a>]<br></li>
<li>Arrows in the DPBP5 proÔ¨Åle indicate the position of the new absorption peaks , the D-Ala-D-Ala containing muropeptides M5 , GlucNAc-MurNAc-L-Ala-D-Glu-m-dap-D-Ala-D-Ala ; D45 , GlucNAc-MurNAc-L-Ala-D-Glu-m-dap-D-Ala-m-dap ( D-Ala-D-ala ) - D-Glu-L-ala-MurNAc-GlucNac ; and T445 , GlucNAc-MurNAc-L-Ala-D-Glu-m-dap-D-Ala-m-dap - [ D-Ala-m-dap ( D-Ala-D-Ala ) - D-Glu-L-Ala - MurNAc-GlucNac ] - D-Glu-L-Ala-MurNAc-GlucNac .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12354237" target="_blank">12354237</a>]<br></li>
<li>Almost 2y3 ( 45 genes ) of the genes activated by NtrCyNac are members of transport operons , which were expressed even in the absence of specific inducing compounds in the medium .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11121068" target="_blank">11121068</a>]<br></li>
<li>Interestingly , Lrp and Nac also act antagonistically at the gltBD promoter , which , like serA , is activated by Lrp and repressed by Nac ( Ernsting et al. , 1993 ; R. A. Bender and R. A. Muse , personal communication ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12123449" target="_blank">12123449</a>]<br></li>
<li>Such a role for Nac in reducing metabolism in response to nitrogen limitation is consistent with the earlier observations that Nac represses both gdh and gltBD , encoding glutamate dehydrogenase and glutamate synthase respectively ( T. J. Goss et al. personal communication , Camarena et al. , 1998 , Muse and Bender , 1998 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12123449" target="_blank">12123449</a>]<br></li>
<li>Mutations in nac suppress the growth defect of strains BK and L * K Nac has various known targets in E. coli , including gltBD ( T. J. Goss et al. , personal communication ) and gdh ( Schwacha & Bender 1993 ; Camarena et al. , 1998 ; Muse and Bender , 1998 ) , both of which it represses , and codBA ( Muse , 1996 ) , which it activates .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12123449" target="_blank">12123449</a>]<br></li>
<li>As already noted , Nac was known to repress gltBD and gdh , and activate codBA ( T. J. Goss et al. , personal communication ; Muse , 1996 ; Camarena et al. , 1998 ; Muse and Bender , 1998 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12123449" target="_blank">12123449</a>]<br></li>
<li>Unlike LysR , Nac apparently does not bind a ligand , which implies that it is constitutively active ( 16 , 63 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11528004" target="_blank">11528004</a>]<br></li>
<li>When expressed from the glnB promoter on a plasmid , Nac had no effect on the rate of cell growth in the presence of casein hydrolysate , but caused a modest inhibition of cell growth on medium lacking glycine or serine whether the medium was nitrogen rich or relatively nitrogen poor .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12123449" target="_blank">12123449</a>]<br></li>
<li>The growth of Ntr constitutive strains in the presence of serine or glycine is not quite as vigorous as the growth of derivatives lacking Nac in the absence of serine or glycine , which may indicate the involvement of another Nac target .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12123449" target="_blank">12123449</a>]<br></li>
<li>The regulation of the anabolic pathway leading to the formation of glycine and C1 units by Nac in Ntr constitutive strains may represent a non-physiological , adventitious regulation by Nac when it is expressed at levels never normally seen in cells .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12123449" target="_blank">12123449</a>]<br></li>
<li>It may prove to be the case that , in wild-type cells , GlnK is never completely inactivated by the UTase/UR regardless of the environmental conditions and , thus , in nature Nac is never expressed at the levels reached in our experiments .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12123449" target="_blank">12123449</a>]<br></li>
<li>If Nac provides a beneÔ¨Åt to cells by enabling the coordinated reduction of metabolism in response to nitrogen starvation , then there should be some environmental conditions in which this advantage is readily discernible in otherwise wild-type cells .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12123449" target="_blank">12123449</a>]<br></li>
<li>This result , together with the high level of GDH activity detected in wild-type cells grown in L-glutamine , strongly suggests that in some conditions , repression of the gdhA promoter by Nac can be overcome by a still unknown mechanism .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9785451" target="_blank">9785451</a>]<br></li>
<li>When expressed from this promoter on a multicopy plasmid , Nac resulted in a severe growth defect in wild-type cells grown under nitrogen-limiting conditions , but had little effect on the growth of cells grown under nitrogen-excess conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12123449" target="_blank">12123449</a>]<br></li>
<li>The intracellular concentration of glutamine regulates-the-activity of the UTase/UR , which controls the PII and GlnK uridylylation state , regulating the activity of NRII and the expression of Nac .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12123449" target="_blank">12123449</a>]<br></li>
<li>Effects of Nac expression in WT cells in deÔ¨Åned liquid media .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12123449" target="_blank">12123449</a>]<br></li>
<li>These experiments suggest that Nac was directly responsible for inhibiting the growth of the cells and could do so even in the presence of GlnK and PII .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12123449" target="_blank">12123449</a>]<br></li>
<li>A Bender , personal communication ) seemed to be involved , as Nac was found to repress serA expression 10-fold in cells lacking PII and GlnK .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12123449" target="_blank">12123449</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , it should be possible to isolate mutations that render NRII ( NtrB ) resistant to control by both PII and GlnK , and we predict that such mutations will result in the growth phenotype associated with the absence of both PII and GlnK , as Nac would be highly expressed and repress serA in such cells .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12123449" target="_blank">12123449</a>]<br></li>
<li>Higher mRNA levels in the first strain in experiments a -- f are indicative of Nac activation , whereas higher levels in the first strain in experiments c -- h are indicative of NtrC activation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11121068" target="_blank">11121068</a>]<br></li>
<li>Nac activation of other operons , e.g. , ompF and opp , was less clear and may be caused by indirect effects .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11121068" target="_blank">11121068</a>]<br></li>
<li>Nitrogen limitation activates the yeaGH operon two - to fourfold , but it is not clear whether regulation requires NRI or Nac ( 176 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11528004" target="_blank">11528004</a>]<br></li>
<li>NRI activates nac expression , and then Nac impairs this activation ( 32 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12730324" target="_blank">12730324</a>]<br></li>
<li>NRI activates 54-dependent promoters , while Nac activates 70-dependent promoters .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11528004" target="_blank">11528004</a>]<br></li>
<li>Nac is under Ntr control and activates EœÉ70-dependent promoters .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23531166" target="_blank">23531166</a>]<br></li>
<li>In K aerogenes , Nac activates the transcription of hutUH , puzP , ureDABCEFG , ar.d dadAB [ 5,6 ] , whereas represses gdhA , gltBDF , and nac itself [ 5,7,8 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11814655" target="_blank">11814655</a>]<br></li>
<li>Nac has been most intensively studied in Klebsiella aerogenes , where it activates genes for histidine , proline , urea , and D-alanine catabolism and represses glutamate dehydrogenase ( 16 , 80 , 106 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11528004" target="_blank">11528004</a>]<br></li>
<li>The transcriptional-regulator Nac accounts for many of these differences in regulation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11528004" target="_blank">11528004</a>]<br></li>
<li>This nitrogen regulation is not mediated by the known regulators that respond to nitrogen limitation , Nac or NtrC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12460564" target="_blank">12460564</a>]<br></li>
<li>Although the function of this gene has not been conÔ¨Årmed , microarray analysis has revealed that ydcS , and the entire ydcSTUV operon , is positively regulated by the nitrogen assimilation control protein Nac ( 93 ) , which induces genes required for nitrogen scavenging under nitrogen-limited conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15576800" target="_blank">15576800</a>]<br></li>
<li>The nitrogen assimilation control ( Nac ) protein activates transcription of s70-dependent genes , whereas NtrC activates transcription of s54-dependent genes .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11121068" target="_blank">11121068</a>]<br></li>
<li>Transcription of most is apparently activated by NtrC in conjunction with s54-holoenzyme , but transcription of some ( ' 9 operons ; 25 genes ) appears to depend on the adapter Nac in conjunction with s70-holoenzyme .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11121068" target="_blank">11121068</a>]<br></li>
<li>Control of Nac speciÔ¨Åc activity is probably not involved in nitrogen source-speciÔ¨Åc modulation , since intracellular metabolites in K. aerogenes do not regulate its activity ( 40 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12446648" target="_blank">12446648</a>]<br></li>
				<label class="ACT_collapse_similarity" for="act_similarity_37">
Our data also show that in nitrogen-limiting conditions Nac is involved in the transcriptional repression of the gdhA gene ( encoding glutamate dehydrogenase ) except when L-glutamine is used as the only nitrogen source .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9785451" target="_blank">9785451</a>]<br></label>
<input id="act_similarity_37", type="checkbox">
<div class="ACT_similar">
<li>Our data show that Nac is involved in the transcriptional repression of the gdhA gene in N-limiting conditions except when L-glutamine is used as Nsource .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9785451" target="_blank">9785451</a>]<br></li></div>
<li>In contrast , under N-limiting conditions , Nac will repress asnC , therefore reducing the level of AsnA , and asparagine will be only synthesized by AsnB .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11814655" target="_blank">11814655</a>]<br></li>
<li>In Klebsiella aerogenes , Nac protein is able to repress gdhA transcription during N-limiting conditions [ 3 ] ; however , GDH activity is not repressed in Salmonella typhimurium [ 4 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9785451" target="_blank">9785451</a>]<br></li>
<li>FEMS Microbiology Letters 167 ( 1998 ) 51 ^ 56 Transcriptional repression of gdhA in Escherichia coli is mediated e Nac protein by th Laura Camarena * , Sebastian Poggio , Norma Garc√®  a , Aurora Osorio Departamento de Biolog√®  a Molecular , Instituto de Investigaciones Biome√®dicas , Universidad Nacional Auto√®noma de Me√®xico , A.P. 70-228 , Me√®xico 04510 D.F. , Mexico Received 3 March 1998 ; revised 28 July 1998 ; accepted 31 July 1998 Abstract In this work we show that the nac gene from Escherichia coli is transcriptionally active , and that its expression is dependent on NRI ( NtrC ) and sigma-54 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9785451" target="_blank">9785451</a>]<br></li>
				<label class="ACT_collapse_similarity" for="act_similarity_42">
