<li>All rights reserved First published online as a Review in Advance on May 1 , 2003 GLOBAL AND REGULATION IN ESCHERICHIA COLI Larry Reitzer Department of Molecular and Cell Biology , The University of Texas at Dallas , Richardson , Texas 75080-0688 ; email : reitzer@utdallas.edu CONTENTS 56 56 56 56 57 59 59 60 61 64 65 INTRODUCTION ... 1 PHYSIOLOGICAL CONTEXT ... 1 Nitrogen Sources ... 1 Ammonia Assimilation and Intracellular Nitrogen Donors ... 1 Quantitative Nitrogen Requirements ... 1 NITROGEN LIMITATION AND THE NTR RESPONSE ... 1 Proteins Required for General Nitrogen-Limited Growth ... 1 Regulation of GS Activity ... 1 The Ntr Regulatory Cascade ... 1 Differential Expression of Ntr Genes ... 1 Functions of the Ntr Response and Nac ... 1 THE œÉ 54 REGULON : ITS FUNCTION AND RELATION TO THE NTR RESPONSE ... 1 Properties of œÉ 54-Dependent Genes ... 1 The Functions of œÉ 54-Dependent Genes ... 1 METABOLIC INTEGRATION : NITROGEN ASSIMILATION AND CARBON METABOLISM ... 1 66 66 67 67 0066-4227/03 / 1013-0155 $ 14.00 155 INTRODUCTION A group of scientists , which included Lavoisier , gave the name azote ( without life ) to the major inert component of air -- a name that is still recognizable in many nitrogen-containing compounds .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12730324" target="_blank">12730324</a>]<br></li>
<li>Tel. ( 48-22 ) 659-7072 , ext. 1310 ; Fax ( 48-39 ) 121-623 ; e-mail : monikah@ibbrain.ibb.waw.pl Abbreviations : aa , amino acid ( s ) ; AMV , avian myeloblastosis virus ; Ap , ampicillin ; Azs , O-diazoacetyl-L-serine or azaserine ; [ SGal , [ 5-galacto-sidase ; Ble , bleomycin ; bp , base pair ( s ) ; cbl , cysB-like gene ; CysB , transcriptional activator of cysteine regulon ; Djk , L-djenkolic acid ; Ec , Escherichia coli ; Ka , Klebsiella aerogenes ; kb , kilobase ( s ) or 1000bp ; LysR , activator of lysine regulon , the prototype of LysR-type transcriptional regulators ; Km , kanamycin ; MCS , multiple cloning site ( s ) ; Nac , nitrogen assimilationcontrol protein ; NAS , N-acetyl-L-serine ; nt , nucleo-tide ( s ) ; OAS , O-acetyl-L-serine ; OASL , O-acetyl-L-serine ( thiol ) - lyase ; oligo , oligodeoxyribonucleotide ; ORF , open reading frame ; PAGE , polyacrylamide-gel electrophoresis ; PCR , polymerase chain reaction ; R , resistant/resistance ; RBS , ribosome-bindingsite ( s ) ; tsp , transcription start point ( s ) ; wt , wild type ; [ ] , denotes plasmid-carrier state .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8529872" target="_blank">8529872</a>]<br></li>
<li>Nac activates codBA ( cytosine-metabolism ) , ydcSTUVW ( putative putrescine-transport and catabolism ) , nupC ( nucleoside-transport ) , gabDTPC ( Œ≥ - aminobutyrate transport and degradation ) , dppABCDF ( dipeptide-transport ) , and fklB-cycA ( 100 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12730324" target="_blank">12730324</a>]<br></li>
<li>Nac also activates codBA ( b0336-0337 ) , a putative polyamine-transport/catabolic operon ( b1440-1444 ) , ( b1932 ) , ( b2393 ) , and-yedL nupC fklB cycA ( b4207-4208 ) and represses serA ( b2913 ) and gltBDF ( b3212-3214 ) ( 50 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12446648" target="_blank">12446648</a>]<br></li>
<li>BLS1 ( gabC nac ) consistently had about twice the activities of SR1 ( gabC ) with aspartate or GABA as the carbon source , which suggests that Nac impairs expression during carbon-limited growth .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12446648" target="_blank">12446648</a>]<br></li>
<li>The intracellular concentration of glutamine regulates the activity of the UTase/UR , which controls the PII and GlnK uridylylation state , regulating the activity of NRII and the expression of Nac .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12123449" target="_blank">12123449</a>]<br></li>
<li>To obtain direct evidence that Nac is involved in Ec repression of gdhA transcription , the chromosomal nac gene was disrupted with a kanamycin resistance cassette ( see Section 2 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9785451" target="_blank">9785451</a>]<br></li>
<li>The cycA gene ( b4208 ) , which encodes a transporter for D-ala , is under Nac control and the ddp operon ( b1483 -- 88 ) , which encodes a transporter and a specific dipeptidase for - ala - - ala ( 10 ) , is under NtrC control .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11121068" target="_blank">11121068</a>]<br></li>
<li>Furthermore , Nac , an Ntr protein , represses two Lrp-activated operons , serA and gltBD ( 12 , 35 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12730324" target="_blank">12730324</a>]<br></li>
<li>Nac protein represses asnA transcription To obtain evidence of a possible role of the Ntr system in the control of asnA transcription , we transduced the asnA : : uidA-aadA allele into the strains MX902 and MX4002 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11814655" target="_blank">11814655</a>]<br></li>
<li>In this work , we show evidence supporting the idea that the Nac protein is involved in the negative control of the expression of the asnA and asnC genes .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11814655" target="_blank">11814655</a>]<br></li>
<li>6 The nitrogen assimilation control ( Nac ) protein represses asnC and asnA transcription in Escherichia coli 1 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11814655" target="_blank">11814655</a>]<br></li>
<li>The nitrogen assimilation control ( Nac ) protein activates transcription of s70-dependent genes , whereas NtrC activates transcription of s54-dependent genes .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11121068" target="_blank">11121068</a>]<br></li>
<li>These genes specify GS , the regulators NRI and Nac , several transport systems , and a few catabolic operons .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11528004" target="_blank">11528004</a>]<br></li>
<li>If Nac activates other œÉS-dependent genes , then nitrogen limitation might induce other stress response genes .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23531166" target="_blank">23531166</a>]<br></li>
<li>Most Ntr genes have either a 54-dependent promoter , which requires nitrogen regulator I ( NRI ; also called NtrC ) , or a 70-dependent promoter , which requires Nac .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12446648" target="_blank">12446648</a>]<br></li>
<li>The transcriptional regulator Nac accounts for many of these differences in regulation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11528004" target="_blank">11528004</a>]<br></li>
<li>Our data also show that in nitrogen-limiting conditions Nac is involved in the transcriptional repression of the gdhA gene ( encoding glutamate dehydrogenase ) except when L-glutamine is used as the only nitrogen source .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9785451" target="_blank">9785451</a>]<br></li>
<li>These regulators also activate expression of another transcriptional activator , Nac .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23531166" target="_blank">23531166</a>]<br></li>
<li>Sometimes Ntr gene-expression also involves a 70-dependent transcriptional activator , Nac , itself the product of an Ntr gene .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12446648" target="_blank">12446648</a>]<br></li>
<li>Transcriptional control of patD expression : œÉS and Nac Gene profiling analysis suggests that Ntr control of patD expression requires Nac ( Zimmer et al. , 2000 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23531166" target="_blank">23531166</a>]<br></li>
<li>To gain insight into the response of E. coli to environmental challenges at the expression level , global gene-expression analyses using DNA microarrays ( Rhodius et al. 2002 ; Khodursky et al. 2003 ) were widely used , e.g. to characterize the responses to exposure to hydrogen peroxide ( Zheng et al. 2001 ) or to elucidate the involved gene regulatory circuits , e.g. by the central regulators of nitrogen metabolism NtrC and Nac ( Zimmer et al. 2000 ) or by the sigma-factor of the general stress response œÉS ( Weber et al. 2005 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17273855" target="_blank">17273855</a>]<br></li>
<li>Such a role for Nac in reducing metabolism in response to nitrogen limitation is consistent with the earlier observations that Nac represses both gdh and gltBD , encoding glutamate dehydrogenase and glutamate synthase respectively ( T. J. Goss et al. personal communication , Camarena et al. , 1998 , Muse and Bender , 1998 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12123449" target="_blank">12123449</a>]<br></li>
<li>In K. aerogenes , besides GDH , some enzymes involved in nitrogen metabolism are controlled by Nac .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9785451" target="_blank">9785451</a>]<br></li>
<li>These results led us to hypothesize that one role of GlnK is to limit Ntr gene-expression under conditions of nitrogen limitation , and that one role of Nac may be to co-ordinate the reduction in metabolism during nitrogen starvation by inhibiting an important ana-bolic pathway .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12123449" target="_blank">12123449</a>]<br></li>
<li>We hypothesize that Nac is part of a physiologically important response to nitrogen starvation that results in the co-ordinated reduction in metabolism and the maintenance of metabolic potential .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12123449" target="_blank">12123449</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul><br>
			<label class="collapse_SIT" for="_5"><font size="5px">Nac binding site</font></label>
				<input id="_5" type="checkbox">
				<div class="SIT"><br><ul><li>According with this proposal , a gel mobility shift assay revealed that the Nac protein binds the asnA-asnC control region ( Fig. 4 ) , suggesting that Nac may recognize at least one of these sites .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11814655" target="_blank">11814655</a>]<br></li>
